```

In this code, we first define the cv::Point and cv::Rect objects. We then use the `cv::Rect::contains()` function to determine whether the point is inside the rectangle. 

If the point is inside the rectangle, the output will be "Point is inside the rectangle.", otherwise it will be "Point is outside the rectangle."

Assuming you have the following custom `Point` and `Rect` structs:

```c++
struct Point {
    int x;
    int y;
};

struct Rect {
    Point tl; // top-left corner
    int width;
    int height;
};
```

You can define a `contains` function for the `Rect` struct to check if a `Point` object is inside the rectangle:

```c++
bool Rect::contains(const Point& p) const {
    return p.x >= tl.x && p.y >= tl.y && p.x < tl.x + width && p.y < tl.y + height;
}
```

In this implementation, the function checks if the `x` and `y` coordinates of the `Point` are greater than or equal to the `x` and `y` coordinates of the rectangle's top-left corner (`tl`), and if they are less than the sum of the top-left corner's coordinates and the rectangle's width and height, respectively.

To use the `contains` function to check if a point is inside a rectangle, you can do:

```c++
Rect rect{ {10, 20}, 50, 40 };
Point point{ 25, 30 };

if (rect.contains(point)) {
    std::cout << "Point is inside the rectangle." << std::endl;
} else {
    std::cout << "Point is outside the rectangle." << std::endl;
}
``` 

